  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article is a practical, tutorial‑style guide aimed at developers who run Docker locally. Its core thesis is that local development environments are often the weakest link in a security chain, so developers must treat them with the same rigor as production systems. It walks through concrete risks—unprotected local networks, Docker’s default bypass of host firewalls, and accidental secret leakage—and offers hands‑on mitigations such as using isolated Docker networks, configuring UFW (or macOS firewall) with tools like ufw‑docker, and adding runtime checks for placeholder secrets. The tone is informal yet instructional, peppered with warning emojis and recurring metaphors of “leaky faucets” and “open doors” to frame security gaps. The piece targets developers who build and test containers on personal machines, providing step‑by‑step commands and code snippets in JavaScript, Rust, and Go.",
